revision.text:
'''Waritakegata Sekkan''' (割竹形石棺) is a type of [[coffin]] from the [[Kofun period]].

[[File:Asuka Museum Sekkan.jpg|250px|thumb|Anfukuji Stone Coffin (rearmost, reconstructed)<br />{{ill|Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum|ja|大阪府立近つ飛鳥博物館}}]]

== Overview ==

It was made in imitation of the carved-out {{ill|Waritakegata Mokkan|ja|割竹形木棺|1=Waritakegata Mokkan}}, with a circular cross-section and vertically cut ends. Rope suspension projections were sometimes attached, and stone pillows were crafted inside. Most examples measure between 2 and 3 meters in length. They first appeared in the [[4th century]] (early [[Kofun period]]) and were produced in areas such as {{ill|Kagawa Prefecture|ja|香川県}}. The {{ill|Funagata Sekkan|ja|舟形石棺|1=Funagata Sekkan}} (boat-shaped stone coffin) is considered a variant, and the waritakegata sekkan is thought to have been used prior to it.<ref>Sugiyama Shinsaku, "Waritakegata Sekkan" / Esaka Teruya et al. (2005), p. 432</ref>

== Examples of Waritakegata Sekkan ==

* Three coffins from {{ill|Kaitenyama Kofun|ja|快天山古墳}}, a keyhole-shaped Kofun located in Kurikuma Higashi, Ayauta Town, Marugame City, Kagawa Prefecture.
* A stone coffin located at {{ill|Anfuku-ji (Kashiwara)|ja|安福寺 (柏原市)}}, said to have been excavated from {{ill|Tamateyama Kofun Cluster|ja|玉手山古墳群}}, specifically from Tamateyama Mound No. 3 in Kashiwara City, Osaka Prefecture.

== Notes ==

<references />

== References ==

* Esaka Teruya, Serizawa Chosuke, Sakazume Shuichi (eds.), *Shin Nihon Kōkogaku Ko Jiten*, New Science Publishing, 2005, ISBN 4-8216-0511-2.
* Supervised by Nagahara Keiji, edited by Ishigami Eiichi et al., *Iwanami Nihonshi Jiten*, Iwanami Shoten, 1999, ISBN 978-4-00-080093-8.

