== Overview ==

It was made in imitation of the carved-out {{ill|Waritakegata Mokkan|ja|割竹形木棺|1=Waritakegata Mokkan|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with a circular cross-section and vertically cut ends. Rope suspension projections were sometimes attached, and stone pillows were crafted inside. Most examples measure between 2 and 3 meters in length. They first appeared in the [[4th century]] (early [[Kofun period]]) and were produced in areas such as {{ill|Kagawa Prefecture|ja|香川県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The {{ill|Funagata Sekkan|ja|舟形石棺|1=Funagata Sekkan|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (boat-shaped stone coffin) is considered a variant, and the waritakegata sekkan is thought to have been used prior to it.<ref>Sugiyama Shinsaku, "Waritakegata Sekkan" / Esaka Teruya et al. (2005), p. 432</ref>

== Examples of Waritakegata Sekkan ==

* Three coffins from {{ill|Kaitenyama Kofun|ja|快天山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a keyhole-shaped Kofun located in Kurikuma Higashi, Ayauta Town, Marugame City, Kagawa Prefecture.
* A stone coffin located at {{ill|Anfuku-ji (Kashiwara)|ja|安福寺 (柏原市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, said to have been excavated from {{ill|Tamateyama Kofun Cluster|ja|玉手山古墳群|1=Tamateyama Kofun Group|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, specifically from Tamateyama Mound No. 3 in Kashiwara City, Osaka Prefecture.

