{{citation needed|Waritakegata Sekkan}}
{{translated page|ja|割竹形石棺|version=52376962|comment=Imported full ja history}}

'''Waritakegata Sekkan''' (割竹形石棺) is a type of {{ill|Coffin|en|Coffin|WD=Q184418|lt=Coffin|1=Coffin}} from the [[Kofun period]].

[[File:Asuka Museum Sekkan.jpg|250px|thumb|Anfukuji Stone Coffin (rearmost, reconstructed)<br />{{ill|Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum|en|Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum|WD=Q4557237|lt=Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum|1=Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum}}]]

== Overview ==

It was made in imitation of the carved-out {{ill|Waritakegata Mokkan|ja|割竹形木棺|1=Waritakegata Mokkan|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Waritakegata Mokkan|13=User:Immanuelle/Waritakegata Mokkan|qq=}}, with a circular cross-section and vertically cut ends. Rope suspension projections were sometimes attached, and stone pillows were crafted inside. Most examples measure between 2 and 3 meters in length. They first appeared in the {{ill|4th century|en|4th century|WD=Q8099|lt=4th century|1=4th century}} (early [[Kofun period]]) and were produced in areas such as {{ill|Kagawa Prefecture|en|Kagawa Prefecture|WD=Q161454|lt=Kagawa Prefecture|1=Kagawa Prefecture}}. The {{ill|Funagata Sarcophagus|ja|舟形石棺|1=Funagata Sarcophagus|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Funagata Sarcophagus|13=User:Immanuelle/Funagata Sarcophagus|qq=}} (boat-shaped Sarcophagus) is considered a variant, and the waritakegata sekkan is thought to have been used prior to it.<ref>Sugiyama Shinsaku, "Waritakegata Sekkan" / Esaka Teruya et al. (2005), p. 432</ref>

== Examples of Waritakegata Sekkan ==

* Three coffins from {{ill|Kaitenyama Kofun|en|Kaitenyama Kofun|WD=Q11491385|lt=Kaitenyama Kofun|1=Kaitenyama Kofun}}, a keyhole-shaped Kofun located in Kurikuma Higashi, Ayauta Town, Marugame City, Kagawa Prefecture.
* A Sarcophagus located at {{ill|Anfuku-ji (Kashiwara)|ja|安福寺 (柏原市)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anfuku-ji (Kashiwara)|qq=}}, said to have been excavated from {{ill|Tamateyama Kofun Cluster|ja|玉手山古墳群|1=Tamateyama Kofun Group|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamateyama Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamateyama Kofun Group|qq=}}, specifically from Tamateyama Mound No. 3 in Kashiwara City, Osaka Prefecture.

